 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=yales>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 1355<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/5/03 12:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=348.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Okay</span><hr size=1> DL...<br>
I don't think the numbers add up the way you propose.<br>
<br>
Let us consider your case: Failure to Achieve Orbit (FAO), to which I would add the variant Failure to Achieve Non-Crappy Orbit (FANCO).<br>
<br>
Combustion engined Sea Dragon and nuclear thermal (LB-GCNR variant) engined Liberty Ship are both designed for mid-ocean launch. So let us start at mid-Pacific - thousands of kilometers from any populated areas.<br>
I am using English units because I am most comfortable with them. <br>
<br>
------------------------------------------------<br>
Sea Dragon with 1,200,000 pounds Payload to LEO<br>
===<br>
Launch Weight:  39,600,000 pounds Gross (Wet with Payload)<br>
<br>
Stage One: 25,520,000 pounds Gross (Wet mass)<br>
-- Fuel: 22,660,000 pounds<br>
-- Hardware: 2,860,000 pounds (Dry mass)<br>
<br>
After burnout, first stage travels less than 500 miles to splashdown (If a failure leaves it attached to upper stage then distance would be MUCH less). The only possible casualties would be a albatross or two.<br>
-------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Stage Two: 12,980,000 pounds (Wet)<br>
-- Fuel: 11,814,000 pounds<br>
-- Hardware: 1,166,000 pounds (Dry)<br>
<br>
Note that only near the end of the burn, with almost dry tanks, would any populated areas be at any risk.<br>
-------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
If The Sea Dragon fails to achieve stable orbit at burn-out<br>
you would have an impactor composed of 1.2 million pounds of payload and 1.2 million pounds of rocket <br>
<br>
- or total of 2.4 million pounds<br>
<br>
Flammable materials would be little to none.<br>
<br>
----------------------------------------------------<br>
Liberty Ship with 2,000,000 pounds of Payload to LEO<br>
<br>
===<br>
Launch Weight:  6,000,000 pounds Gross (Wet with Payload)<br>
<br>
Stage One: 4,000,000 pounds Gross (Wet mass)<br>
-- Fuel: 2,400,000 pounds<br>
-- Hardware: 1,600,000 pounds (Dry mass)<br>
<br>
If the atomic Liberty Ship fails to achieve stable orbit at burn-out you would have an impactor composed of 2 million pounds of payload and 1.6 million pounds of rocket and  1.2 million pounds of liquid hydrogen<br>
<br>
- or total of 4.8 million pounds<br>
<br>
of which over a million pounds is violently flammable materials.<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Bottom line is that a failed Sea Dragon would impact a city with half the mass of a nuclear Liberty Ship and million pounds less hydrogen. <br>
<br>
BTW - I don't understand this statement you made about the Liberty Ship: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>has only just over 1000 tons of pure hydrogen on board with<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong> no oxidiser present</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The horribly flawed Liberty Ship design uses the liquid hydrogen turbopumps from the space shuttle. These little brutes are two stage devices. The first stage spins it compressor from heated exhaust propellent parasitized from downstream. The second stage is combustion driven. Liquid oxygen and hydrogen are burned and plumbed into a gas turbine.<br>
These pumps are the size of automobile engines yet put out 60,000 horsepower at 10s of thousands of RPMs! The ship use TWENTY-ONE of these bad boys. (As an aside, a failure of any of them would created an explosive mass of hypersonic schrapnel that would 86 any rocket.) At burn-out, a Liberty Ship would carry MANY tons liquid oxygen.<br>
<br>
======================================<br>
In addition to smacking a city with twice the mass and 500 tons of nasty liquid hydrogen, it could release on the order of  100s of billions of millicuries of fission products (mostly short-lived)- <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>very</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> bad for the exposed individuals<br>
<br>
You stated: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>.. I have no reason to believe that a significant proportion would not be from radiation sickness from exposure to the intense shorter lived FP’s <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes, I agree that acute radiation poisoning would be nasty, but longer term effects would also be there. Just for one example, somewhere around 10 billion millicuries of radioiodine would be released. This is a potent trigger for thyroid cancers - particularly in children.<br>
<br>
Not wishing (at least in this thread <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   ) to get into a side discussion of the risks of long-lived FP contamination, I will just note that under regulations, the level of contamination would require long term evacuation and restricted use of dusted area.<br>
<br>
yale<br>
<br>
