<br>
One of the other factors to keep in mind is that every single launch vehicle currently in operation in the united states (and abroad, I believe, with the exception of the soyuz, but dont quote me)  INCLUDING the space shuttle, is equipped with 'range safety'  which is basically a big explosive designed to blow the ship to smitherines in the atmosphere to prevent it from crashing and exploding on the ground. <br>
<br>
<br>
There were a couple of posts here that bothered me:<br>
<br>
&quot;We need nuclear powered spacecraft, and the sooner we have them the better. I realize systems like Orion are not perfect, but they are available. It will be a real downer if we need such a system and we don’t have it available. Extinction sucks. &quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;My opinion is that nuclear powered atmospheric rockets could be justified for certain purposes. And we need to build a nuclear powered launching system, JUST in case we need it. So far we, the world has detonated just under 500 mega-tons of nuclear bombs ABOVE GROUND. So i think that using a few more kilo-tons worth for space travel is justified. I think we need ships capable of diverting asteroids at a SAFE distance from earth. I also think we need a sustainable outpost off planet, either the moon , mars, or possibly orbital, incase of some super virus or unforseen natural problem arrises. Survival of the species is simply the most important goal ever. All other considerations are secondary.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
You seem to be taking it for granted that the only way to evacuate anyone from earth is with nuclear power.<br>
<br>
Existing chemical systems may be inadequate for such needs right now, but they are far closer to being adequate than any hypothetical nuclear system.<br>
<br>
XCOR aerospace (where I worked for 6 months) is building a reusable rocket that should be able to take a payload into space every day or two at full operational pitch.<br>
<br>
Burt Rutan at Scaled Composites is working on a similar system.<br>
<br>
John Carmak (of DOOM fame) of armadillo aerospace is pursuing a similar goal.<br>
<br>
Transorbital is working on putting a payload on the moon.<br>
<br>
<br>
It seems to me that given the massive body of knowledge and experience in the world relating to chemical rocket systems, if we really needed to get off the planet, we'd ride chemical systems, not nuclear.  There are simply no engineering teams that I know of capable of constructing anything like the liberty ship.  I dont know enough about nuclear rockets to say that its categorically impossible or even seriously flawed, but I dont know who can build it.  <br>
Whatever.  I'm not too worried about it.  I'm confident that nothing like it will fly from earth in my lifetime. <br>
My personal goal is to walk on mars.  Yeah, its far fetched, but I'm confident that state of the art is at the point where it's not ridiculous to begin designing a manned interplanetary mission.  It wont happen for (my guess) at least 10 years, but I think it'll happen in my lifetime.  <br>
<br>
A ground launched nuclear vessel, though?  <br>
<br>
Please dont misconstrue.  I think nuclear vessels have their place.  I just think their place is outer space.  The ISP of chemical systems just isn't great enough to permit a mission to (say) alpha centauri.  Whereas a (properly designed, space assembled and launched) nuclear vessel may very well be able to complete that mission in a few decades.<br>
<br>
I'm glad to see that you're all still around...  Its been a while.  I wasn't sure yales in particular would still be here.  Is PO gone?  I'm assuming so...  Havn't read any posts of his yet.  Kinda a relief.<br>
<br>
-Nato out <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=yales>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 1365<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/10/03 10:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=348.topic&index=44>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Okay</span><hr size=1> Stilgar, you old Freman!<br>
