microscopic to the millions of pounds of thrust range. They are in serial mass production. We could likely scale them up any number of times and/or create large clusters.<br>
<br>
On the nuclear side, other than table-top models or pure &quot;paper&quot; designs, none exist. Only a handful of experimental proof-of-concept, non-flyable engines were tested 30+ years ago. These were quite touchy with problems with fuel erosion and vibration. The largest of these was fired for some minutes at only 250 thousand pounds of thrust - low by current standards. The Isps were only twice current engines.<br>
<br>
As to other nuclear designs, they exist only on paper.<br>
<br>
If for some reason we needed hurry up and do some heavy lifting, then it would be chemical rockets that would do it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hillbillydave>hillbillydave</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 25<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/10/03 8:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=348.topic&index=48>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Lets build a small, reusable spaceplane</span><hr size=1> You may be right. If we had to build a ship 'today' we would probably use chemical because we 'know' it would work :-) <br>
