lift themselves off the ground easily. Their radiation<br>
shielding  is not too heavy for them to fly. *<br>
They are practical, and reusable, but very expensive.<br>
Nuclear thermal nerva type solid core fission rockets are completely legal,practical and sane for ground launch operations.*<br>
It is possible to garuntee no radioactive material<br>
spills if a nerva type nuclear rocket crashes during<br>
a launch  by placing a berylium metal  moderated reactor inside  a very strong steel casing which will  also  double<br>
as the nuclear radiation shield around the  reactor<br>
core.* This can also be done by casting the U-235 core<br>
as one single large  donut shaped large hunk of heavy metal.*<br>
Gas core nuclear fission rockets however are unsuitable<br>
for ground launch operations. GNRs are suitable only for<br>
in space uses.<br>
The nerva class solid core  nuclear fission rocket however<br>
is well suited for ground launch operations.<br>
